Proposed law requires the commission to administer the program based on the uniform
guidelines promulgated by the commission.
Proposed law requires the funds be used for pursuit intervention training or the purchase of
pursuit intervention technology and devices to enhance pursuit safety, including but not
limited to:
(1) GPS tracking projectiles.
(2) Vehicle-stopping nets or tethering systems, such as the Grappler.
(3) Remote-controlled tire deflation devices.
Proposed law authorizes the commission to receive funds, grants, donations, or other
assistance from any source, including federal funds from the Hwy. Safety Improvement
Program, the Edward Byrne Memorial Justice Assistance Grant Program, the National Hwy.
Traffic Safety Administration, the Homeland Security Grant Program, the Community
Oriented Policing Services Technology and Equipment Program, the Community Policing
Development Microgrants Program, and the La. Dept. of Transportation and Development
in furtherance of the state's Strategic Hwy. Safety Plan for the purposes of this program.
Proposed law requires the commission prioritize grant applications from agencies that have
integrated pursuit technologies into policy that emphasize law enforcement safety by
reducing manual deployment risks.
Designates proposed law as the "Sergeant Grant Candies Officer Safety Act".
(Adds R.S. 40:2401.4)
